\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line Although the programme meets the minimum standards with respect to criteria 3-9\'2C the evaluator believes that the Honours in Divinity programme cannot be accredited because the programme design is fatally flawed \'28Criterion 1\'29 and admission \'28Criterion 2\'29 is inappropriate to a Bachelor Honours Degree qualification.\line \line The programme has a dual aim\'3A  to take students with an undergraduate degree in any field and provide them with \'22a bridge to theology\'22\'3B and to \'22deepen their expertise in research capabilities to enable them to progress to a Master\'27s degree in Divinity\'22. \line \line It is conceptualised as a programme for students without a Bachelor\'27s degree in Theology. It offers in effect a broad introduction to the field of theology as a whole. This is evident from the way the curriculum is structured\'2C the broad scope indicated by module titles featuring the words \'22Survey\'22 and \'22Introduction\'22\'2C and the module outlines provided. The modules cover all the traditional theological sub-disciplines. The HEQF conceives the Bachelor Honours Degree as a qualification that \'22serves to consolidate and deepen the student\'27s expertise in a particular discipline\'2C and to develop research capacity in the methodology and techniques of that discipline\'22. It presupposes prior knowledge in that discipline or an allied discipline. As the evaluator states\'2C the proposed programme \'22seeks a short-cut that does not take the need for specialization within the field of theology into account and under-estimates the need for discipline-specific training\'22 in a qualification of this nature. The students will simply not have the background to engage with the subject matter at Level 8\'2C and the subjects offered are not at the appropriate level. \line \line The application states that the programme is based on the premise that \'22these learners are able to integrate theology into their previous learning and the disciplines they were involved in\'2C together with their life experience and learning within the context of the church\'22. It does not and cannot specify which disciplines are involved. The evaluator states that while the institution is correct in observing that a transfer of knowledge is possible in the field of theological studies since it is by nature highly inter-disciplinary\'2C a blanket transfer of skills from any one discipline to another is not possible. It is not even possible within the traditional sub-disciplines constituting Christian theology. The gap would be even greater in the case of students with qualifications in business\'2C science or health than in the case of those with a bachelor\'27s qualification in the arts\'2C humanities or social sciences. A false assumption about knowledge transfer therefore underlies the programme.\line \line The evaluator points out that the aims of broad introduction and the development of what the institution terms \'22practical theological research skills at an Honours degree level\'22 are in conflict with each other. While students may develop some methodological skills\'2C it is simply not intellectually credible to expect them to develop the required level of discipline-specific competence and to engage with the vast literature available at a level sufficient to enable them to pursue Masters studies on completion of the degree. \line \line The evaluator does\'2C however\'2C recognise the need for a broad introduction to theology for graduates with a non-theological background\'2C but such needs could be met by means of an Advanced Diploma that does not lead to a master\'27s programme.\line \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the programme should not be accredited \cell \pard 

